---
title: "Existential Risk Prevention as Global Priority"
author: "Nick Bostrom"
domain: "existential-risk.org"
url: "https://existential-risk.org/concept.pdf"
pubDate: 2013-12-17
takeaway: "Frames the prevention of existential risks, including misaligned AGI, as a supreme global public good and economic priority."
---

Nick Bostrom’s paper is a profound, philosophically rigorous call to action that completely changes how we should evaluate long-term technological progress. As an engineer building in the age of artificial intelligence, it is incredibly easy to get swept up in the immediate, day-to-day hype of training larger models, building faster APIs, and shipping new features. Bostrom forces us to step back and look at the bigger picture: the existential risks, particularly from misaligned AGI, that threaten our entire species. He argues that preventing these risks is a supreme global public good, and one that should command significant economic and political resources, rather than being treated as a fringe science-fiction concern.

For those of us on the ground building these technologies, this isn't just an abstract philosophical debate—it is a design mandate. It means we cannot treat safety and alignment as some secondary compliance checklist to be ticked off right before a launch. We have to build robust, ethical constraints directly into our engineering culture, our development pipelines, and our deployment strategies from the very beginning. It forces us to ask hard, uncomfortable questions about the unintended consequences of the systems we are putting into the wild, and to realize that our responsibility as builders extends far beyond just hitting our quarterly product targets.

### What stuck with me

* **Global public goods**: Preventing human extinction must be recognized as an ultimate global economic priority that transcends private or national interests.
* **The alignment mandate**: Safety and alignment principles must be integrated into the core architecture of advanced software systems from day one.
* **Responsibility of builders**: Engineers and founders must look beyond immediate product metrics to address the broader societal consequences of their creations.
